SIMPLE: diamagnetic
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Diamagnetic
<hw>Di`a*mag*net"ic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to,
or exhibiting the phenomena of, diamagnetism; taking, or being of a
nature to take, a position at right angles to the lines of magnetic
force. See <er>Paramagnetic</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Diamagnetic attraction</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Attraction</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Diamagnetic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Diamagnetic
<hw>Di`a*mag*net"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Any substance, as bismuth,
glass, phosphorous, etc., which in a field of magnetic force is
differently affected from the ordinary magnetic bodies, as iron; that
is, which tends to take a position at right angles to the lines of
magnetic force, and is repelled by either pole of the magnet. Contrasted
with <contr>paramagnetic</contr> and
<contr>ferromagnetic</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Diamagnetically</ent>⟦br⟧
